<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF206-955-166  </DOCNO><DOCID>06 955 166.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Modern Office Technology  Jan 1989 v34 n1 p45(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>MIS functions overlooked during mergers. (News andamp; Trends)andM;</TITLE><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The American Management Association and the Business ManagementServices Division of Control Data survey 109 companies about theimpact of a merger or acquisition on the human resources functionand the MIS function of the new organization.andP;  The survey showsmerging the financial systems is the top priority.andP;  Humanresources comes in third, followed by payroll in fourth place andbenefits in fifth.andP;  Most respondents said they did not have theinformation they needed.andP;  There are six major problems inretrieving data: employees do not know what information isavailable, systems and methods of organizing data areincompatible, there is a lack of pre-acquisition planning in thehuman resources and operations areas, the human resources andoperations areas receive low priority, the need for informationexceeds staff capacity and employees of the acquired companyresist retrieving information.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Control Data Corp. Business Management Services Div. (surveys).andO;Ticker:    CDA.andO;Topic:     MISMergerSurveyAmerican Management AssociationAcquisition.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>